"We resolve factual controversies in favor of the nonmoving party, but only when there is an actual controversy, that is, when both parties have submitted evidence of contradictory facts. We do not, however, **in the absence of any proof**, assume that the nonmoving party could or would prove the necessary facts.” *Little v. Liquid Air Corp*., 37 F. 3d 1075 (5th.Cir. 1994) (emphasis added) *See also Ultrasound Imaging Corp. v. Am. Soc. of Breast Surgeons*, 358 F. Supp. 2d 475, 483 (D. Md. 2005) (“Significantly, Ultrasound has submitted no discovery materials for the Court's consideration; thus, by definition, Ultrasound has failed to raise a disputed material fact regarding the allegedly stifled competitive environment and its injurious effect on consumers.”); *Anderson v. Liberty Lobby, Inc.*, 477 US 242, 248-252 (1986) (A defendant who submits a “mere scintilla of evidence” does not create a “genuine issue of material fact.”)

anyways now that im properly awake;

first of all, it's not my job to enforce court-established deadlines. i'm not a court officer or anything of the sort. the fact you submitted it past the court's deadline is a fact, and fortunately for us the judge hasn't decided whether or not he'll stick to that deadline. matter remains that, even if he didn't, summary judgement, or anything akin, is inappropriate.

that is because of the second reason: there is no summary judgement in petitions. petitions, in matters of habeus corpus in particular, are governed by the mrlm, not the mrcp. in the mrlm, the only way for petitioner to get anything akin to summary judgement is if the state willingly does not contest the petition or fails to file the requested court documents in response within the set timeframe. needless to say, our circumstances here fall outside of that, and there is no such event where the state has "waived its right to challenge" petitioner's factual allegations because, put simply, any processes or procedures beyond initial filing, response, and final ruling are all optional and at the presiding judge's discretion.

and even if, for reason, that weren't the case, no self-respecting judge can reasonably accept this writ of habeus corpus where the petitioner's submitted exhibits so readily contradict the factual allegations laid out in their own petition: particular the very crucial allegations laid out in paragraph 2, which alone largely feeds petitioner's argument that the arrest was absurd. paragraph 2 is, in whole, dismantled by petitioner's own exhibits. in accepting this petition, the court would be giving way to aspiring vigilantes to break the law, and then hand-wave it under the guise of "absurdity" which, as i pointed out in my response, "[will] turn the State into a storm of bullets in which law enforcement officers- those who are expected to protect the very communities in which you reside, will be unable to discern criminals from otherwise well-meaning citizens."
